data.text: Today we got a lot done. We completed the information sent to the google sheet and we also got the settings menu to work to send it to a certain google sheet id.

(11/08) One of our goals for today was to work out how we can distinguish the balls from the cubes using a camera. We decided that one of the easiest ways that we could differentiate between the balls and the cubes was to use the color difference (cubes are yellow and balls are white) in order to determine where on the screen each of them are. We found that the major difference in color between the white balls and the yellow cubes was the green channel of color, where the white balls have a significant amount of green and the blocks have almost no green present. When taking a threshold of the green mask, it can be determined very accurately the relative position of the balls to the cubes.

card.name: Plan and create the Autonomous code

data.text: Today, we did the broad - scope Autonomous planning today.  We ultimately decided that we would have three main paths: two where we can get one or both of the debris selection, or one from the other side of the cube where we one get one debris selection.  With the addition of a Drive Recorder, programming for Autonomous will be done much faster. We plan on ending near the crater closest to our sides of the Lander as to be better positioned to score right away in TeleOp.

Today, we started work on how to integrate a new vision package, BoofCV, with the LinearOpMode structure.  This is preferable to last year's OpenCV because BoofCV's native language is Java, as opposed to OpenCV's hassle from a native C++ Structure.  BoofCV also has faster complex image manipulation methods than OpenCV.  The testing structure so far involves trying to compose a Bitmap (compiled image) on command from Gamepad1. We tested a structure where a picture is deliberately taken, but that proved not to work.  Next meeting, we hope to test a structure of just scanning a preview frame on command.

data.text: Began to work on database collection for the elements in the app and sending information to a google sheet.
Today I worked on the UI for the scoring app. Nearly finished... just need to find out how to place hints on a spinner correctly.
(10/7) We refined and simplified our drive, turn, and one wheel turns.  We also re-implemented null check methods from last year to create an easier and more dynamic programming environment.
(10/2) Today, I put the layout of the app together. There will be two 'pages' - one with the autonomous and the other with tele op and endgame.

(10/2) Today, we implemented a fillable picture to indicate to scouters a relative amount of the zone filled to speed up the scouting process.  We also decided on a left-right scrollable layout to simplify the input system for scouters as well.

(9/25) We began testing our one wheel drive routine, and found that we had a few issues with the speed of one of the motors. Our main theory is that the encoder target is the opposite direction to what the motor's power is telling it to go, causing the PID to ramp up really high to attempt to correct. We will try to fix this soon.
(9/23) Our two wheel "turn on a dime" turn routine was added to our library. The two wheel turn worked exactly as intended. We began work on our 1 wheel turning routine.

(9/20) Today we finally discovered the issue with the autonomous drive routine was actually nonexistent. We realized that we had just gotten super unlucky with all of the testing setups that we had been using, either having motors that were bad or in the case of our backup robot having drastically different tensioning on the left and right sides of the drivetrain. We finally realized that this was our problem all along after testing on our production robot from last season and realizing that it drove quite straight with our drive routine, and after retensioning the wheels on our test bot we replicated our results we called it good. Next meeting we will work on our turning.

(9/27) Today, we laid out a sample layout for the Scouting App.  In this process, we determined our goal to be speed and simplicity.  Instead of forcing scouters to guess an exact number of elements in scoring zones, we decided to create a slider to represent how full the scoring zone was.  We are also looking to add more authentication processes and to simplify team selection by preloading a list of teams and matches to allow scorers to pick more easily.
(9/27) The HTML output is now reformatted to properly display labels.  Also, in the event of a late comment, a date tag can be added in and the parser will move the action to that day.

The ideal system found to complete this goal was the built in branching system with Git, the Version Control System that we were already using.  To start, 1 branch for each member of the software team was created and the master branch was preserved.  Hopefully, the individual branches can be used for experimental work on different robot systems, while using code review and testing strategies to ensure that only reliable software gets pushed to the master branch.  More of the controls team will have to be writing robot code before this card can officially be moved to testing.  After some testing, we will determine whether or not it is working and loop back around to another stage of development if need be.

data.text: Created most of the data collection for JSON files and was able to read the records of the trello boards.

Today, the formula was discovered to have the incorrect input being fed in, and after re-evaluating the process needed to back drive the distance driven, the function inputs were corrected.  Now, the program is moving to a point to be tested with normal drive and turn functions implemented to provide a sense to the accuracy of the recorder.

[general distance to encoder fomula.gif](https://trello-attachments.s3.amazonaws.com/5b71beda9b895f312b9bf867/5b9405f9494f112a6426e5eb/b60cc0a98357ff6cabcc138ec648435f/general_distance_to_encoder_fomula.gif) [general distance to encoder fomula.gif](https://trello-attachments.s3.amazonaws.com/5b71beda9b895f312b9bf867/5b9405f9494f112a6426e5eb/b60cc0a98357ff6cabcc138ec648435f/general_distance_to_encoder_fomula.gif) 

This is the normal formula used to convert a distance to encoder counts.  To create the back driving formula, we started with encoder counts and ran the formula backwards to the input matching the recorded movement.

Today, I worked on resolving a motor speed difference issue that has been causing our motors to stop at different times from each other due to not running the correct speeds. It seems that the motor mode has some effect on this, as when in RUN_WITHOUT_ENCODERS the robot will drift one way, while in RUN_WITH_ENCODERS or RUN_TO_POSITION results in the robot drifting the other way. I was unable to resolve this issue today.
We wrote out a possible outlook for our final product. We discussed the structure and format of our program.
Began the first test on parsing the JSON file. Eventually, we were able to gather information using JSON keys. 9/16

The control lock error was fixed, and both motors were fixed (They originally didn't exit Reset Encoder mode).  However, the formulas needed revision, as the movements recorded didn't match the expected distances traveled.  Corrections coming soon.
